🔗 4. Connect IntelliJ → Ubuntu VM (best method)
Option A (BEST): SSH + Git workflow
Step 1 — install Git in VM
sudo apt install -y git
Step 2 — create project locally (IntelliJ)
New Project → Maven → Java
Group: com.example
Artifact: demo-app
Step 3 — push to Git (GitHub / Bitbucket)

From IntelliJ:

VCS → Enable Git
Commit + push
Step 4 — pull in VM
git clone <your-repo>
cd your-project
Option B (faster iteration): SSH directly

From Windows terminal:

ssh devops@<VM-IP>

You can:

build
run
debug logs
⚙️ 5. Build Java app from IntelliJ

Inside IntelliJ terminal:

mvn clean package

This creates:

target/app.jar
🐳 6. Deploy to VM (simple method)
Option 1: SCP (quick)
scp target/app.jar devops@<VM-IP>:/home/devops/
Option 2: Git pull (cleaner)
commit → push
in VM: git pull
🚀 7. Run app in VM
java -jar app.jar
🐳 8. Next step (Docker — very important)

Create Dockerfile:

FROM openjdk:17-jdk-slim
COPY target/app.jar app.jar
ENTRYPOINT ["java","-jar","/app.jar"]

Build in VM:

docker build -t my-app .
docker run -p 8080:8080 my-app
☸️ 9. Later: Kubernetes deployment

From VM:

kubectl apply -f deployment.yaml
